The big comeback of the Czech loser is approaching.
Pavel Francouz has been called up to the NHL
Czech ice hockey goaltender Pavel Francouz, who is going through a difficult period in his career, is returning to the NHL.
The thirty-year-old Pilsen native will be on the bench and could soon be in goal.
The former goaltender of Litvínov, Plzeň or the Russian Chelyabinsk was injured during the preparation for the NHL in October of this year.
He was benched in the middle of the game against Vegas and has not played in the NHL since.
The incident happened as the experienced goalkeeper moved from one post to the other.
"Pavel Francouz will be out for approximately three to four weeks with a lower-body injury," the Avalanche announced at the beginning of October.
His return to the NHL net ended up lasting more than two months.
He was called up from the farm on Sunday morning U.S. time, where he had caught four duels and showed his old form.
In the AHL, he made 94.5% of his saves.
The graduate of Plzeň hockey wants to finally break through and prove that he belongs in the best league in the world.
In the last season, he had hip problems and in the shortened pandemic season, he didn't catch a single game.
In the NHL, "Francík" played in 36 games, with a save percentage of 92.3%.
