Lenka Kabrhelová talks to iRozhlas editor Dominika Kubištová.
I respect the soldiers and the army (I am probably not affected by the memories of the Czechoslovak People's Army that older generations experienced), but the Czech Republic cannot benefit from compulsory military service.
We don't even have large stocks of equipment that could be grabbed by the newly trained, we don't even have modern equipment for the current professionals, and on top of that, modern equipment is always more complicated, so the skills of the reservists will be rapidly lost over time.
To that, modern conventional conflicts, where anyone can be deployed, will play out very quickly, there will be no time to retrain anyone.
Finally, the reservists/territorial defence are of great importance for countries like Ukraine, where mass guerrilla warfare is conducted and it is also an explicit necessity for deterring the enemy.
In the Czech Republic, it will only work in a conflict of such size and intensity that guerrilla warfare will be irrelevant, and we do not have the right geography for that.
Mainly we don't have individual skills.
It's not even the worst of it.
The worst part is that half of them are playing like they have it.
Then you find yourself in a situation where you look like an idiot, who two minutes ago couldn't hit an empty net, and you drive into an attack on your own between 2 or even 3 Swiss players, and you ask yourself "what the hell do you think is going to happen now?"
Of course, they'll treat him like an average taxpayer.
The situation with this skill of "beating a defender" is so bad that I caught myself being genuinely surprised when I saw our attacker beat one of the opponent's players.
The first swallows
The Covid-19 pandemic is slowing down, but experts do not expect any major change in the coming weeks.
The pressure on hospitals will persist for some time, according to statistical models, and a new unknown has been added to the pandemic equation: the omicron variant, which is very likely to spread faster than the currently predominant Delta.
At the same time, it is not yet possible to say with absolute certainty whether it can cause a more severe course, to what extent it is helped by vaccination or post-infection immunity acquired from a previous illness.
This week, however, an unexpected phenomenon on the plus side entered the COVID equation: the possibility of treatment.
The new drug, the antiviral molnupiravir, has arrived in the Czech Republic. This reduces the risk of a severe course of the disease and associated hospitalisation by a third, and it is possible to be treated with it at home.
And soon, it should be joined by the Paxlovid drug from Pfizer, which from the current results reports a success rate of up to 85 percent.
The first delivery of molnupiravir to the Czech Republic has, in addition to the hope of expanding the portfolio of tools useful in the fight against the coronavirus pandemic, highlighted the question of how the Czech administration is prepared for the arrival of new drugs.
As mentioned, the first to reach Czech patients will be Merck's molnupiravir.
The company ended up at the front of the pack in part because the drug was in development long before the current pandemic began, with the goal of finding a treatment for a viral disease of horses in South America.
