How to not drown in a box tsunami
You unwrap the gifts under the Christmas tree, and all of a sudden you're home buried in boxes and packaging?
The "waste" is being re-used by online shops that are short of packaging materials.
A map was created of stores that will accept your used boxes.
And not just at Christmas.
All packaging materials are designed to withstand repeated handling.
That's why it's a shame to treat them as disposable.
Anyone can bring cardboard boxes, plastic or paper padding to the participating store (the map of the KAMsNIM.cz project contains almost 150 of them) by agreement.
This will support small businesses, reduce the amount of waste produced and avoid overflowing blue bins.
Shops themselves welcome the packaging, which is currently in short supply on the market, and also the saved money, as packaging cardboard has risen in price by 50 per cent in the last period.
In the eyes of customers with an ecological mindset, I am strengthening my brand.
One of these stores is TIERRA VERDE, a manufacturer of eco-cosmetics and eco-cosmetics.
The boxes and packing material are brought to us in Popůvky near Brno by individuals who have collected them at home, but we also hear from companies with whom we have arranged regular pick-ups of discarded cardboard.
We'll use everything when we pack orders from our e-shop.
Together, individuals and companies are creating a more considerate world.
Our wish is to preserve the resources and beauty of nature for future generations, says Petra Lopušníková from Tierry.
However, the www.KAMsNIM.cz application shows not only collection points for packaging waste.
It serves as a search engine, if you need to get rid of anything (where to take sorted household waste, where to drop off expired medicines, tyres, retired electronics, batteries, light sources, bulky waste, etc.).
All waste can end up in the right place, and in addition, reusable items can find their second home.
The project map already contains more than 100,000 such places.
"Over time, more and more collection yards, re-use centres, textile containers, food banks, charity shops, SWAPs and other places that help to find a use for things that would otherwise become waste are being added to it," adds Miroslav Kubásek, one of the authors of the application from the Ukliďme Česko association.
It seems wrong to me that today's technology is so simple and fool-proof that children who use computers or phones to play games don't learn basic computer skills.
Recently there has been an issue (mainly in English articles) that college students don't understand the concept of folders on a computer.
Because apps like Google Photos or Apple's Photos app, or really mobile phones in general, just hide the underlying filesystem with folders and put everything on one screen in the app.
They can use the technique from childhood, but most of all, they should learn something.
Let's rewrite history, seriously
Emmanuel Macron unveiled the priorities of France's EU presidency - starting in January - over the weekend and it was grand.
Macron spoke for over an hour, during which he revealed the logo of the presidency, called for the protection of Europeans - at work, on the street - and mentioned so many actions that they cannot be done in half a year.
French politicians love it, and so do the voters.
Macron's supporters who straddle the right and left agree on little, but on Europe they do.
And there will be new elections for the head of state in France in April.
The election calendar has also influenced the priorities.
The French leader, among other things, mentioned that historians should write "one history of Europe" and that France is ready to create the conditions for such work by historians.
A number of commentators were quick to criticise Macron's pro-European propaganda and rewriting of history.
In fact, they are trying to prevent the rewriting of history.
The far-right candidate for the French presidency, Éric Zemmour, is currently touring France with the thesis that the Vichy regime, which collaborated with Hitler during World War II, was not so bad, and he is doing quite well with the French.
Let's take Macron's idea of one history book seriously and not look at what's happening in France.
Is it needed?
In European countries, students often learn history as a story of us versus them and never as a story of the whole.
Spaniards, French and Czechs are learning who beat whom in which battle.
If they don't have a wise cantor, they won't learn the wider context of the event.
