Christmas book recommendations
The Christmas double issue, which comes out on December 20, will feature the traditional literary supplement.
Along with her, cultural tips will also come out.
We are adding these books to the digital edition for you, our subscribers, so that you will have enough time to buy the books as Christmas gifts.
The prose texts follow on from the previous collection of Petříček Sellier & Petříček Bellot.
Another helping of observations of the world and descriptions of ordinary things with extraordinary poetic awareness, depth and atmosphere.
In his second novel, photographer Šesták tried to capture the essence of a small town and Czech society.
It is a story of returning to one's roots, which turns out to be only a longed-for illusion.
The bohemist and comparatist transfers the fairy tale of Little Red Riding Hood into the setting of a contemporary village.
Her delivery of brutality outstrips the folk versions and escalates into a horror of emotional emptiness.
And that the path back to instincts is shorter than one is willing to admit.
The author's penultimate novel tells a much less sentimental story about returning from emigration than we are used to hearing.
Those who stayed and those who left know too little about each other to make it work.
Trains start to run according to the new timetable, in some places the operators have changed
From Sunday, trains will be running on the railways according to the new timetable.
The biggest change is the change of carriers on some routes, such as between Ústí nad Labem and Kolín, where instead of Czech Railways, RegioJet is starting to run.
For most lines, only the departure time will be changed, and in some cases, the route will be slightly changed.
There will also be dozens of new trains on the tracks.
The transport companies started selling tickets during the autumn.
Czech Railways plan to operate an average of 6,783 passenger services per day in the new timetable, including an average of 478 long-distance trains per day.
The trains will travel approximately 118 million kilometres during the new timetable.
In addition to domestic connections, the new timetable will also include routes to Germany, Poland, Slovakia, Hungary, Austria, and Switzerland.
The company will introduce dozens of new trains along with the new timetable.
The main new feature will be InterJet trains, which will run on routes from Prague to Cheb.
The transport company will send more new trains to northern Moravia and western Bohemia.
The transport company will also, as is traditional, raise the price of tickets next year, by an average of 3.2 per cent.
The railways factor in inflation into their tariffs every year.
The biggest change in RegioJet's timetable is the introduction of the R23 Ústí nad Labem – Mělník – Nymburk – Kolín line.
The carrier will replace České dráhy here following success in the Ministry of Transport's competition.
RegioJet will operate a total of 16 connections on the route every day, eight in each direction.
Other changes affect long-distance services between Prague and Brno, which from Sunday will also stop at Havlíčkův Brod, Žďár nad Sázavou and Kolín stations.
Leo Express kept its 16 connections, two return connections to Slovakia and also weekend connections to Krakow.
According to spokesperson Emil Sedlařík, the transport company also tried to keep the timetables of its long-distance trains as similar as possible despite the planned work.
Without major changes, the operation of Arriva trains and other carriers should also continue.
There will be a change of carrier on some regional lines as well.
Changes are in store for passengers, for example, in Českolipsko, where instead of Czech Railways, the Trilex trains of the German company Die Länderbahn will run on the line from Mladá Boleslav via Česká Lípa to Rumburk.
Passengers will also be able to use the unified rail ticket for the second year.
As with Czech Railways, their price will increase by 3.2 percent due to inflation.
I have to disagree.
Are we not supposed to learn to see things from the other person's point of view?
Everywhere we hear about how much they had to fight for their rights, how they were oppressed and had to work hard and die.
In my life I've never heard a lesson from the perspective of the slave owner or from that time, no one is defending it, just condemning it.
No one tells you in school that blacks often sold blacks into slavery and that they were often the worst slave owners.
No one will teach you in school that the colonizers often bought the land from the Indians; they will only tell you how brutally we, the Europeans, wiped them out, while they were killing each other long ago.
I spent some time in the USA as well, directly in schools, both in the north and in the south.
I have not come across anyone deliberately covering up facts, but I have heard before that it does happen and I think it's a problem, which I do not deny (e.g. WW2 atrocities are quite taboo in Japan).
My point was more that history isn't black and white and that we have a tendency to look at it through a modern lens without understanding.
History is not interested in someone's feelings, it is what it is, and I think it is a fatal mistake to judge without looking at things from that time.
On the other hand, we should learn from it and never repeat it.
By the way, while we're on the subject of the southern states, yes, the Confederate flag and famous slave-owners are quite popular there, on the other hand, they also had some successes and it seemed absurd to me to reject them.
Moreover, the North was not much better, as many people idealise it today.
And a lot of people also forget that not everyone in the South was a slave owner and a lot of things were also opposed to them.
I wouldn't compare this to the Russians, they deliberately leave out certain facts, they lie and manipulate, and our perspective doesn't even exist there (there was even a video on YouTube from a TV station where they cut off someone who started talking about our legionnaires and 1968).
What I found ridiculous in US schools was the rise of Marxism and the idealization of communism, something their country has never experienced.
Overall, I felt that at some universities it was terrible, those students were quite radicalized and the schools often supported them in that.
And when I imagine that these people will be much older one day, it makes me a bit sick to think that this could be the voice of the majority, because it is among the young and in the ruling elite.
I think that, for example, feminism has already achieved what it had to and it is no longer about the same thing, it has become radicalised.
