TV has fallen out of love with the Christmas movie, with 200 premieres this year
Los Angeles - Cinemas, television stations and streaming platforms in the United States and other English-speaking countries have fallen under the trend of Christmas films and this year they are premiering a record-breaking more than two hundred of them for their viewers.
This was counted by the operator of the film database IMDb.
The genre of Christmas family and romantic films has scored with the public in recent years and has significantly increased the number of viewers, so more and more of these films are being made.
This year, four times as many Christmas films were made as in 2011 and twice as many as five years ago.
The IMDb database only counts those films that have the word Christmas in their title, so there are actually many more Christmas films.
The films people traditionally associate with Christmas have always existed.
In the Czech Republic, this period is mainly associated with fairy tales, and around the world, films such as Home Alone, It's a Wonderful Life and the classic Christmas story Life is Beautiful from 1946 are popular.
However, the real boom of Christmas films began in 2009, when the American cable TV network Hallmark came up with a special film series, the BBC server recalled.
Her "Countdown to Christmas" project at the time included four movies and was very successful.
This year, the network started its viewers in the Christmas mood as early as October 22 and will present a total of 42 Christmas films.
Competitor network Lifetime has 35 new Christmas-themed films on its schedule this year, and popular streaming services like Netflix are also contributing to the total.
"In this magical time, the story doesn't matter so much, it's important that there are a lot of Christmas trees in the background and that it's snowing," said Brandon Gray, the author of the book I'll Be Home for Christmas Movies (Na vánoční filmy budu doma), jokingly describing this genre.
"It's a form of escapism for the viewers and a way to feel a little bit of peace for two hours in the midst of all of this holiday madness and the madness of the world we've been living in for the last few years," Gray added.
According to him, for example, the Hallmark channel uses the same recipe for its films, which is uniform, but successful.
You have two people who fall in love, but then there's some misunderstanding about half an hour before the end, which is resolved and they kiss.
That's how it goes round and round, and as long as all the movies look and feel the same, people will watch one after the other, Gray adds.
