In my childhood, they punished me with a wooden spoon.
It was never because of marks, it was mostly because I repeatedly refused to listen and misbehaved (read instead of going to bed, argued with my brother, etc).
At the same time, I have never been punished without warning, my mother always first threatened that if I did it again, I would get a spanking (sometimes even after another "scoop" of the pan, she would only bring it and put it down so that I could see it).
Only after I repeatedly refused to listen, did I get a couple of spankings (through clothing).
Personally, I think physical punishment (in a reasonable manner and to a reasonable extent) is beneficial as a child responds to it much more than words.
I think the important part is the warning section, because it gives the child a choice of whether or not to disobey and get the punishment, or to improve and not get the punishment.
I was usually only given a warning before I started to listen.
Defence of the system
When prominent Czech lawyer and constitutional judge Vojtěch Cepl answered a journalist's question in 1999 about what the Czech constitution meant to him - whether it was a sacred document to which one swore allegiance and which was taught in school from an early age, or rather an agreement that could be changed if necessary - he certainly favoured the first interpretation.
Once, we agreed in the constitution on the democratic rules of our life, which, at the same time, define who we are as a state and its citizens, and we should be careful with changes.
And imagine this: Some nations even like their rules.
Just like the Czechs love dumplings with pork and cabbage, Vojtěch Cepl commented at the time.
Recently, however, there has been an increasing opinion among lawyers that the Czech Constitution needs to be changed.
Year after year, it is tested by situations that its creators (including Vojtěch Cepl) could not predict, for example by the behaviour of the directly elected president.
However, Cepl was right about one thing.
All we know about such documents shows that political interventions in their texts must be well thought-out.
The Institute must be understood and actively defended, only then can it be the key to overcoming most of the crises that societies have faced throughout history.
The constitution is, among other things, a set of rules of governance, which set the boundaries of the game for politicians.
We fear that power will be abused against minorities or individuals, so we tie the hands of politicians with prohibitions.
At the same time, the constitutional texts also allow politicians to exercise their power.
Covid does not discriminate, several-month-old baby fighting for its life in Brno University Hospital
Even though it is known that the coronavirus is milder in children, there are also severe cases, which the hospital is mainly dealing with lately.
"We know that children are less at risk and less affected than adults, with 2 to 5 per cent compared to adults," said the head of the Clinic of Pediatric Anesthesiology and Resuscitation at the Faculty Hospital Brno and Faculty of Medicine of Masaryk University, Petr Dominik, to Novinky.
The course is often much simpler, lighter, and often without symptoms.
But there are child patients who are severely ill with the coronavirus, which we can see especially in recent times," added Dominik.
According to the doctor, there are dozens of children who need mild supportive care.
It takes place at a pediatric infectious disease clinic.
Only recently have very seriously ill children with coronavirus been admitted to the ICU.
Children with post-Covid syndromes have been in the ward continuously throughout the year, according to the doctor.
"Now, we're seeing an increase in kids with acute COVID pneumonia, that is, pneumonia that requires admission to an intensive care unit," he said, adding that the illness affects not only adults, but also teenagers and even infants as young as a few months old.
There are also children in critical condition due to the coronavirus in hospitals.
"At the moment, we have a child of several months and an adolescent," said the head of the department.
However, she is pleased that the children's hospital at FN Brno has not recorded any child deaths due to the coronavirus.
According to available data, six children aged 0 to 14 years died in the Czech Republic by 6 December.
According to Dominik, a psychologist is an integral part of cooperation in a children's hospital - not just in the COVID-19 department.
At the same time, it points out that just like in adults, vaccination in children also reduces the severity of the disease and at the same time reduces the occurrence of the post-COVID-19 syndrome.
"That's why we recommend the vaccine dose for children," added the doctor.
