Over 60 per cent of voters turned out for the Saturday elections to the councils of four municipalities
People elected new councillors on Saturday in the municipalities of Komňa in the Uherskohradišť district, Lužice in the Most district, Nová Ves in the Liberec district, and in Rovné in the Pelhřimov district.
The number of councillors in these towns has fallen below the number set by law, or the elected council has collapsed.
A total of 99 candidates competed for 28 seats on Saturday.
The average age of the newly elected representatives is 46.7 years.
The oldest of them is 69 years old, the youngest is 33 years old.
The processing of the results of Saturday's elections symbolically closes a rather demanding, but successful year for us.
Four new or repeat municipal council elections and, above all, the closely watched elections to the Chamber of Deputies were held, said the Deputy Chair of the Czech Statistical Office, Eva Krumpová.
She reminded that due to the Covid-19 epidemic, the elections were more demanding in terms of equipment and personnel security.
The Association of Independent Candidates won Saturday's elections in Komňa in Uherskohradišť, with 27.76 percent of the vote and two seats in the seven-member council.
The STAN candidate received 24.84 percent of the vote, which also means two mandates.
Občané pro Komňu also won two seats in the council, receiving 18.52 per cent of the vote.
Jana Křižková, the former mayor of the village, who is a member of the Soukromníci (Privateers) party, was also re-elected to the council.
Komňans achieved one seat in the council as independent candidates.
75.48 percent of eligible voters showed up at the ballot boxes.
In the village of Rovná in the Pelhřimov district, the Pro Rovnou association won.
It received 50.50 per cent of the votes, which means four seats out of seven.
Two representatives from Association of Independent Candidates 1 and one from Association of Independent Candidates 2 were also elected to the municipal council.
Voter turnout was 93.62 per cent.
The repeated elections in Lužice on Mostecku were won again by the Association of Lužice and Svinčice led by Mayor Jindřich John.
It received 56.73% of the vote and, like in 2018, has four seats in the seven-member council.
The second place went to Obec pro lid, which received 43.27 per cent of the votes, and will have three representatives in the council.
76.7 percent of voters went to the ballot boxes.
The independent candidates Naděje pro Novou Ves won the elections in Nová Ves in the Liberec Region ahead of the ANO movement.
59.88% of voters voted for the association of independent candidates and won four seats in the seven-member municipal council.
ANO got 40.12 percent of the votes and strengthened compared to the regular elections in 2018, gaining one more seat and now has three.
Voter turnout was 42.9 per cent.
The State Election Commission will discuss the election results on Monday.
They will then be published in the Collection of Laws.
