Kara-France then defeated Cody Garbrandt.
Nunes celebrated another triumph with her little daughter in the spring, but now, after seven years, she has lost.
That hip, or this hip?
At first glance, it doesn't seem complicated.
In Czech, most nouns express only one grammatical gender, so there is no problem in determining whether it is masculine, feminine or neuter.
Then there is also a fairly large group of nouns for which the gender is not fixed.
Such substantives oscillate between two genders.
When inflected, they take on double endings, and in some cases remain in the uninflected form.
For example, words such as "svízel" or "kyčel" are both masculine and feminine, in the first one they are declined according to the pattern of "stroj" and in the second one according to the pattern of "píseň".
Another group of nouns have different forms in the first singular case, for example: „řádek/řádka“, „kedluben/kedlubna“ or „brambor/brambora“ (in the sense of food).
Both forms are standard, have the same meaning, and are therefore freely interchangeable.
Some terms can differ from region to region, for example "okurka" in Bohemia and "okurek" in Moravia, but in this case the Moravian version is non-standard, and the same is true for other Czech-Moravian word pairs: "příkop" and "příkopa", "kobliha" and "koblih", etc.
Some words that have entered the Czech language from other languages were originally uninflected, but they are gradually taking on Czech endings.
A typical example is the word "image", which is both masculine and feminine, or the word "buffet", which has remained in the middle case without inflection, but in the masculine it has endings according to the pattern of "castle".
