Scattered houses flood the Czech Republic, families do not have the money to finish them
The price of building materials has risen by more than 30 per cent in recent weeks and months.
This has put a lot of people in a difficult situation.
She does not have the means to complete the family houses she has set up and banks are refusing to increase her mortgage loans.
In addition to the cost of materials, the cost of building work is also rising.
People therefore do not have enough money to complete the family homes that have already been set up.
In many cases, banks are refusing to increase their mortgage loans, creating an extremely uncomfortable situation.
At best, people move into makeshift and unpermitted homes.
In the worst-case scenario, the scattered houses are uninhabitable and families are forced to sell them because they cannot afford to pay both the mortgage and the rent," says BHS economist Štěpán Křeček.
We build two to three family homes a year and fifty per cent of the time it happens to us.
It's difficult for us as a construction company because we have to comply with certain things in the contract, even if the materials have become more expensive.
So we are doing it for free," said Zdeněk Slivoň, the owner of a construction company.
A lot of people are just going to have financial problems.
If they calculated that the construction of the house would cost five million, now it will cost seven.
I think some will wait," added Slivoň.
The most expensive materials were copper, iron, and also plumbing and heating equipment.
Construction firms are also battling a shortage of labour.
There is a shortage of construction graduates in the Czech Republic and the influx of foreign workers is being held back by the pandemic.
Only the situation regarding the issuance of building permits is more favourable at this time.
"Building authorities issued 7,675 building permits in October, which is almost 10 percent more than last year," said Křeček.
