A statement from the Workers' Party of Donbass
The Union - yes, the dissolution - no, say the opponents of the dissolution of the Soviet Union in the picture.
Thirty years since the illegal dissolution of the USSR.
On December 8, 1991, the largest geopolitical catastrophe in human history took place.
On December 8, 1991, Boris Yeltsin, Leonid Kravchuk and Stanislav Shushkevich, without any legal authority and in violation of the results of the referendum on March 17, 1991, with the open tolerant attitude of Mikhail S. Gorbachev, secretly, without regard for the people, signed an agreement that “the USSR as a subject of international law and as a geopolitical reality ceases to exist”.
With one stroke of a pen, they "erased" a huge country with almost three hundred million inhabitants.
With the collapse of the USSR, tens of millions of ethnic Russian citizens found themselves abroad.
Russia's population has fallen by ten to eleven million since the early 1990s.
Even without the loss of the non-Russian population of the former Soviet republics we've already lost more people than in both world wars combined!
Earlier, the same people, who in one sitting in the Belovezhskaya Pushcha forest destroyed what had been built over the previous seventy years, betrayed the socialist camp (created at the cost of millions of lives in the Second World War and in the Great Patriotic War).
They deliberately de-industrialised, they slowed down agriculture, they broke away from the largest world power, fourteen republics that were previously economically linked in a single mechanism.
If we look even deeper, we see the impoverishment of the population, the collapse of the economy, science, the military, the rise in crime, inter-ethnic conflicts, the war in Chechnya, all conflicts in the post-Soviet space, a series of Orange Revolutions, the expansion of NATO to the east, the war and the collapse of Yugoslavia, the Arab Spring, the war in Syria - all of this is the result of geopolitical capitulation, first of the socialist camp, and then of the Soviet Union.
There is such a concept in political science as "power vacuum".
Everything that was hastily betrayed and given up was quickly filled and conquered by the NATO countries that accepted our geopolitical capitulation.
And the whole world is still shaken by the events of the end of the 1980s and the beginning of the 1990s.
