How the pandemic has affected intimate life: the number of people under 35 who have not had sex for a whole year is growing
More young adults in the U.S. are living their lives without sex.
It is mostly religious people, says the DailyMail website.
The survey found that the proportion of people aged under 35 who abstained from sex rose from eight to 21 per cent between 2008 and 2021.
Women between the ages of 18 and 35 who say they haven't had sex in the past year are more than ever before.
Other factors have also contributed to the decline in sexually active individuals, according to a survey by the Institute for Family Studies (IFS).
One of them could be the economic effects of the coronavirus pandemic and a higher percentage of unemployment.
But the presence of the media, social networks and video games, which make sex less and less of a priority for young people, may also have contributed.
"Between 2010 and 2018, the share of 18- to 35-year-old men and women reporting no sex in the past year has been growing rapidly," said IFS researcher Lyman Stone.
People in married relationships are more likely to be sexually active, with just 5% of them reporting no sex in the last year in 2021.
It was 29 percent among the unmarried. Stone added that marriage under the age of 35 is only a small percentage.
The decline in sexual activity is also due to the fear of premarital sex and religious beliefs.
While married couples are more likely to be sexually active, the proportion of married and cohabiting men and women aged under 35 is still falling.
Young people's opinion on premarital sex is divided, with about 30% thinking it is a bad thing, while about 70% think it is okay.
"It's true that they're a minority among free-wheeling individuals in this age group, but their behavior is shifting the trend," Stone said of the 30 percent.
Most of those who have a moral problem with premarital sex do so for religious reasons.
Since 2008, the rate of abstinence among singles under 35 who attend religious services more than once a month has risen from 20 per cent to almost 60 per cent.
Among the "less religious," the trend rose from 10 to 20 percent," Stone said.
The decline in sexual activity is also attributed to other factors, such as less social interaction and especially the social drinking of alcohol during the pandemic.
The study also found that the likelihood of sex is lower for people who are unemployed or have lower incomes.
Another reason could be the expansion of digital media, which apparently reduces the need for sex.
People are spending more time online, which is "replacing" this need.
This trend has caught on especially during the lockdown period of the coronavirus pandemic.
The entire COVID vaccination mandate is about whether society should force a portion of the population to behave in a way that they don't want to, but that could save their lives.
It's a pretty tough question, but I'm personally most interested in the question of social conscience.
For example, the question of whether it will be our fault if we don't tell them to do it and they die.
My argument is that we could have certainly been responsible for the death of an 80-year-old man who really didn't know very much, we didn't explain it well to him, he heard some misinformation, and as a result he didn't get vaccinated and eventually caught it and died.
On the other hand, I don't think we can blame the death of a determined anti-vaccination campaigner who shouts alongside the SPD and the Communist Party here about bullying and a totalitarian state.
From the statistics I mentioned, it can be quite clearly inferred that most of the unvaccinated pensioners probably belong to the second group, so they will be able to pay for it themselves.
