The dog, Hugo, is doing his best.
However, Juraj Šajmovič didn't keep an eye on his film.
Czech creators of family comedies have looked to American stories about dogs.
However, they forgot one important thing: the laws of the film business.
After the kitsch film F. Brabec's Gump - The Dog Who Taught People to Live, another film is now vying for the audience's emotions in cinemas, Here We Guard.
Co-writer and director in one person Juraj Šajmovič Jr. freely builds on his previous film Tady hlídám já from 2012.
Returning to the scene is the talking Dachshund, Hugo, along with some familiar characters around him.
Julie and Ivan, the owners of a dying pension in the Šumava mountains, start to invite dog walkers, Julie's father and his partner and most of all her daughter Veronika.
She's no longer a little girl, but a young woman experiencing her first love.
The director and his partner, Beatriz Shamovich (who is also the film's producer), struggled with storytelling techniques in their previous dog film, but at least that one entertained children and a dog.
This time, the creative duo wrote an even weaker script, which evokes a mixture of disgust and feelings of embarrassment.
Let's recap.
Despite being a scientist, Julie succumbs to the darkness of superstition in her desire for a child, and when the right "constellation" occurs, she copulates with her forest engineer, Ivan, anywhere the coordinates dictate - on the hood of a car or a church tower (of course, during an ongoing excursion with a local guide), the retired Colonel Mojmír, despite years of training, shoots his own daughter (Julie) in the forest, who falls into a coma, whereupon she is taken from the hospital by her family, so that a miraculous healing process can take place in the heart of the Bohemian forest with the help of a dog.
Nothing against the cleansing power of nature and the power of animal companions.
Their owners know why they have them.
However, the viewer is amazed at how much content, full of implausible situations and characters, was required to convey this message.
A pair of thieves from the staff, a dog show competition, a South Bohemian charlatan, police officers arriving on a tip to search for "drugs" and discussing herbs over the fertilizing power of bone meal - and, of course, a family that gets drunk in the pension.
When the protagonist, after a long coma, sits at the family table, made up and with a cigar, and demands her father's whisky and a steak as a recovered vegetarian, you can't help but laugh.
On top of that, the creators explain to the viewer that "this sometimes happens after a coma".
Šajmovich's team lacks basic dramaturgical knowledge of working with the text, the ability to build up main situations, a sense for the characters' traits and the point, and directorial guidance.
The acting is uneven, the editing aimless, and the overall impression muddled.
Despite the best efforts of Lukáš Vaculík, Jitka Ježková, and Nela Boudová to keep their parties going, they don't have much to play with.
The only positive aspect of the film remains the poetic shots of the Šumava nature by cameraman Vladimír Holomka and the two dachshunds.
It's not enough to outline a few characters, a flimsy plot, and dog puns, not to mention the more common vulgar words the characters use.
Long-standing membership in the Club of Dachshund Breeders - as in the case of the lady producer - is not an argument either.
For good intentions to promote nature and the friendship between man and dog, one must also have knowledge of the craft, if one wants to tell a believable story.
This did not happen in this case.
There is a bit too much eroticism and a minimum of feeling for the genre in the good family photo.
Even as a commercial for canine therapy, this amateurish piece wouldn't pass muster.
