The Middle East is experiencing unusually dry months.
Winter is the only time of the year when it rains.
"Almost complete absence of rainfall during November, as recorded at some stations, is unusual," the Israel Meteorological Service confirms.
For example, the village of Kfar Giladi in northern Israel reported just six percent of its long-term average rainfall for November.
This week's two-day rainfall was therefore more of an exception.
It's good for us.
It hasn't rained for a long time.
It is also the right Christmas backdrop, rejoiced Nazareth resident Wasim Aškar.
Precipitation in Israel comes almost exclusively in the winter months, is sporadic and irregular.
Forests are dependent on winter rains.
Without them, they dry up and are prone to fires.
It's not just forests, but also drinking water supplies and irrigation for farmers.
Israel's largest freshwater source, the Sea of Galilee, filled to the brim this spring, thanks to three consecutive rainy winters.
Since then the level has been falling.
Water managers have been warning of drought for a long time.
"It is expected that as a result of global warming and climate change, there will be less precipitation here," said Uri Schor, a spokesperson for the Israeli Water Authority, in 2018.
Israel is able to help itself with technologies such as desalination or waste water recycling.
Economically weak countries such as Lebanon, Syria and Jordan are faring worse.
In the streets of Jordan's capital, Amman, water tankers are becoming more common.
The public water supply and private wells are drying up.
"This year I've had a 70-80 percent increase in orders compared to the previous two years," tanker truck driver Imad Suleiman said in September.
In Iran's Isfahan, clashes broke out between farmers and security forces.
The reason for the protests was the drought.
The bed of the local river was completely dry.
The region has experienced one of its driest Novembers in recent years.
