Skiers headed to the mountains over the weekend, where they found plenty of snow and nice weather
Ski resorts in the Czech Republic experienced their first major influx of skiers this weekend.
After the heavy snowfall at the end of the working week, there is no shortage of snow, and some ski resorts have opened as a result.
The downhill skier was not deterred by the requirement to show a Covid certificate at the lifts.
While the tow operators aren't complaining about a lack of customers, some ski rental shops are reporting lower demand for their services than before the pandemic.
Thousands of people took to the cross-country ski tracks and ski runs in the Liberec region over the weekend.
Skiers enjoyed the weather, which offered sunshine and excellent snow conditions today.
"We are satisfied, the opening weekend really started with Friday evening skiing, when we had the first skier on the hill," the director of the Ještěd Sports Area, Jakub Hanuš, praised the interest.
Hundreds of people headed to the Jeseníky Mountains for the first weekend of skiing in the new season.
For example, Ski Aréna Karlov and the centre in Branná in Šumpersko were open.
The weekend attendance was very good, with an estimated 400 people on Saturday and today.
The conditions are great.
Today, the sun was shining and it was about three degrees below zero, so it was perfect, said Rostislav Procházka, a representative of the Branná ski resort, who did not spare the praise.
Ski resort operators can only sell lift tickets to people who are vaccinated or have recently recovered from COVID-19.
With the exception of a few, people are prepared for it and show the required documents, said René Hroneš from the Špindlerův Mlýn ski center to CTK.
"We've only seen a handful of incidents," he added.
Some ski rental and equipment stores are reporting lower interest than before the pandemic.
Fortunately, there is interest in renting skis.
It's not like in previous years, but there are still enough customers, said Alexandra Bokišová from the Skiopava store in Opava.
It is expected to be busier during the ski season.
David Šinták, a representative of the Královéhradecká company Snowbear, also feels that due to Covid, people are not as interested in renting ski equipment as they used to be.
At that time before the pandemic, we were almost on loan.
Compared to the period before the pandemic, we are at about 50 percent, Šinták told CTK.
People, according to him, have become lazy during the pandemic and have learned to sit at home.
In contrast, the rental shop in the Novako area in Boží Dar is experiencing high demand.
They started renting out skis a week ago, and interested parties now have to order them in advance.
"We're starting to rent skis this weekend, but people have already been calling in advance, so we expect a lot of interest, just like last year," said facility operator Pavlína Nováková.
According to her, the interest in ski school is also comparable to the period before the epidemic.
