New timetables come into effect in Prague from Sunday, mainly affecting suburban services
Passengers on the Prague integrated transport system (PID) can expect several changes from Sunday, which will affect mainly suburban connections.
New lines have been created, some have changed routes, and others have been discontinued.
Mladoboleslavsko is now joining the integrated system.
In the capital, from Sunday, express trains from České Budějovice stop at the Zahradní Město station.
The S7 suburban trains will run on the route from Beroun to Český Brod, passing through Prague Main Station.
The newly opened station in Prague-Zahradní Město will now be served by the R17 express train from České Budějovice and Benešov.
The PID is expanding into other areas.
Among other things, the buses will travel to Světlá nad Sázavou, Blatná near Jesenice, Staré Splavy and Turnov.
Buses in the Mladá Boleslav region will be included, including lines with connections to the Liberec and Hradec Králové regions.
During the integration, 77 lines will be abolished, 37 new lines will be introduced and the operation of 12 existing lines will be adjusted.
A new bus line 405 will depart from Prague's Zličín, travelling all the way to Žatec.
A new direct connection between Prague and Kralovice near Rakovník was also created, replacing the discontinued S53 train line.
There will be strengthened connections from Prague to Rakovník in the morning rush hour and on weekends, with a new express line number 404.
Lines 400 and 410, which run to the Liberec region, have now been included in the PID system.
They depart from the Střížkov metro station, not from the Holešovice train station.
Spine line 400 runs through Mělník, Dubá and Česká Lípa to Nový Bor and selected connections continue to Rumburk or Cvikov.
The additional line 410 runs from Mělník and Dubá to Doksy, Mimoň and Jablonné v Podještědí.
In contrast, the operation of dozens of local lines in Central Bohemia has been cancelled or restricted, including those to Mochov, Dobříš and Rožmitál pod Třemšínem.
All trains leaving Prague at 02:30 have been cancelled.
Long-term restrictions on the lines from Prague to Beroun, Prague to Lysá nad Labem and in the vicinity of Kolín will continue as a result of railway modernisation.
Travellers will also be affected at other locations.
Buses are replacing some of the cancelled train routes or the section of line 420 from Dobříš with connections from Prague, where it is possible to use PID tickets up to Milevsko.
The routes of lines 540 to 543 in Nymburk have been changed, and the routes of some buses on the border of Central Bohemia and Hořovice in the Pilsen region have been adjusted.
