Another government ends and the law on the involvement of municipalities in the selection of a storage site is nowhere to be found
Minister Karel Havlíček’s proposal needs a major overhaul
The government of Prime Minister Andrej Babiš is coming to an end, and the law that was supposed to guarantee the respect of the interests of municipalities and their citizens in the selection and authorisation of a deep geological repository for high-level radioactive waste still does not exist.
The Government Legislative Council interrupted the discussion of the proposal, which the Ministry of Industry and Trade submitted to the government after years of delays.
Its content, however, is in serious conflict not only with the affected municipalities, which are members of the Platform against the Deep Repository, but also with the Association of Towns and Municipalities of the Czech Republic.
Self-governing bodies are expecting a significant strengthening of their decision-making powers in relation to a storage facility, which has been promised to mayors since 2011, when the first work on this legislation began, and which is required by the Czech Atomic Act and the European directive.
We expect that the new government will, in accordance with its coalition agreement, revise the proposal in cooperation with the municipalities.
The draft law from Minister Karel Havlíček, which Platforma has access to, is criticized by municipalities mainly for: The proposed level of involvement of municipalities and the public in the decision-making process on the selection of the site for the storage facility is inadequate and cannot ensure respect for the interests of municipalities and their citizens.
It can only be truly effective if communities or the public can influence whether the process will continue in a given location.
This can be achieved by requiring the Storage Administration to request permission from the affected municipalities before initiating a specific procedure.
The proposed draft of the land-use plan almost completely ignores the involvement of the public and turns the citizens of municipalities into mere statistics in the approval process.
The proposal lacks a system of compensation for municipalities for the entire process of finding and selecting the site for the storage facility, its approval, and operation.
According to today's legal norms, representatives of municipalities do not have many options to defend the interests of their citizens when they are looking for a place for a storage facility.
Only in some permitting procedures can they submit their comments or appeal, but it is the authority or minister who has an interest in issuing the permit that makes the decision.
The potential lawsuit does not have a suspensive effect on the carrying out of survey or construction work.
The co-determination of local authorities, which the Platform is requesting, is a principle that is commonly used in many democratically developed countries and certainly in those that have already advanced in allowing storage facilities, such as Sweden or Finland.
The preparation of the law is yet another failure of the state administration, which hires external law firms to prepare legislation.
In this case, it concerns a contract with the law firm HAVEL & PARTNERS s.r.o., which was entered into by SÚRAO and which follows on from contracts with the lawyer Jan Zemánek.
According to the register of contracts, the total sum for this work is almost 4 million Czech crowns.
Antonín Seknička, deputy mayor of the village of Cejle from the Hrádek area and spokesperson for the Platform Against Deep Storage, said: After the industry ministers, who only pushed the alignment of the position of self-governing bodies with state authorities in the search for a deep storage of highly radioactive waste to their successors, we expect a more significant turnaround from the new government.
We are also offering a helping hand.
We would also like to thank the Association of Municipalities and Towns, which, like the directly affected municipalities in selected locations, views the issue of insufficient rights of municipalities in relation to such a fundamental construction in the same way.
The platform against deep storage brings together 51 members (35 municipalities and towns and 16 associations) in order to promote a change in the state's approach to dealing with spent nuclear fuel and other radioactive waste, which will not be limited to deep storage.
The platform further proposes that the decision on the selection of the location for any storage should be subject to the prior approval of the affected municipalities.
John Goodman's (69) fear forced him to lose weight: He lost 90 kg.
Although he didn't need to change his lifestyle for a long time, he was eventually scared by doctors.
He was told that if he didn't lose the weight, he would die.
And it took up a lot of time.
Goodman lost 90 kg, which is half of his original weight of 180 kg, says The Sun.
He showed off his new look in Los Angeles at the premiere of the animated series The Freak Brothers.
He's a completely different person from the fat guy in the Roseanne sitcom!
John liked to joke that friends and family asked him to lose weight because his large body caused furniture to break.
"I put everything in my mouth," the actor said in a 2018 interview with AARP.
This time, I wanted to do it slowly.
Move, exercise.
I'm getting to an age now where I can't afford to sit on the sidelines, said Goodman, whose transformation is remarkable.
It also depends on what kind of boss and in what context you want to use the word "boss".
If it's some kind of text on a platform that expects readers from the gaming environment, I wouldn't translate it at all.
If it were a formal text, perhaps a university text, I would probably look for ways to describe or explain the boss.
To make matters worse, there are different types of bosses.
For example, in a game like Dark Souls, there are multiple bosses, right? And so a "boss" is something like a lord/ruler of a given level, and then there's the final boss...
In many games, there are hidden bosses (super boss, hidden boss), which are not necessary to defeat in order to complete the game or level, but are often more powerful than the standard boss.
Then there are games like Half-Life, where there are bosses, but the player doesn't fight them directly (Tentacle, Gargantua), and can they be called bosses at all?
And then there are the mini-bosses.
It's not possible to translate the word "boss" into a single word in general. Czech and other languages don't have a solution for this (Catalan is an interesting exception, as it translates the word "boss" as "final opponent").
It is simply a computer-controlled opponent that is more powerful than all previous ones and guards the completion of some level or task for the story or the game in general.
